What:		/sys/devices/platform/cpu_lpm_stats/collect
Date:		December 2024
Contact:	"Mariano Marciello" <mmarciello@google.com>
Description:
		Control node for statistics gathering. Echo 1 to turn on, 0 to
		turn off.

		On read returns whether collection is currently on or off.

		Default value: off.

What:		/sys/devices/platform/cpu_lpm_stats/reset
Date:		December 2024
Contact:	"Mariano Marciello" <mmarciello@google.com>
Description:
		Control node to reset statistics. Echo anything to perform reset.

What:		/sys/devices/platform/cpu_lpm_stats/<power_domain>/residency_data/
Date:		December 2024
Contact:	"Mariano Marciello" <mmarciello@google.com>
Description:
		Each CPU power domain has a folder with statistics for its low power
		mode. This data is read as a single raw value.

		Currently available statistics are:
		 - min 			- minimal recorded residency time
		 - max  		- maximal recorded residency time
		 - average  - average residency time
		 - count		- number of power domain switches recorded
		 - total_residency		- total recorded residency time

		All statistics above, apart from count, are measured in GTC ticks.

		Example usage:
		 cd /sys/devices/platform/cpu_lpm_stats/power-domain-cpu0/residency_data/
		 cat max
		 cat min
		 cat count
		 cat average
		 cat total_residency

What: 		/sys/devices/platform/cpu_lpm_stats/<power_domain>/latency_data/<latency_type>/
Date: 		December 2024
Contact:	"Marcin Wasowicz" <mkwasowicz@google.com>
Description:
		Each CPU power domain has a folder with subfolders with statistics for its
		low power latencies. This data is read as a single row value.

		Currently available latency types:
		 - fw_entry		- low power mode entry firmware latency
		 - fw_exit		- low power mode exit firmware latency
		 - fw_sched_entry	- low power mode entry firmware scheduling latency
		 - fw_sched_exit	- low power mode exit firmware scheduling latency
		 - fw_entry_transition	- low power mode entry firmware transiton latency
		 - fw_exit_transition	- low power mode exit firmware transiton latency
		 - e2e_entry		- low power mode entry end-to-end latency
		 - e2e_exit		- low power mode exit end-to-end latency

		Hardware latencies are not available for CPU power domain referring to single CPU.

		Currently available statistics for particular latency type:
		 - avg 			- average latency
		 - max			- maximal latency
		 - min			- minimal latency
		 - count		- number of power domain switches recorded

		All statistics, apart from count, above are measured in GTC ticks. The count
		statistic is the same for all latency types and equals count statistic from
		residency_data directory.

		Example usage:
		 cd /sys/devices/platform/cpu_lpm_stats/power-domain-cpu0/latency_data/e2e_entry
		 cat avg
		 cat max
		 cat min
		 cat count

